  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara*, an apparent evolution—or tension—in his views on homeland and nationalism emerges between Part 1 and Part 3. In Part 1, Chapter 26 (\"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet,\" also known as *Tarana-e-Hindi*), Iqbal crafts a rousing anthem celebrating Hindustan (India) as a sacred, inclusive homeland blending diverse spiritual legacies, from Chishti and Nanak to biblical prophets:\n\n> Where Chishti first Truth's holy call conveyed,  \n> And Nanak's song of Oneness was displayed,  \n> The land the Tatars for their homeland made,  \n> Which drew Hijaz's sons from desert shade,  \n> **This is my homeland, this land of mine.**[^1]\n\nThis refrain repeats, exalting the land's history, wisdom, and divine favor as a \"paradise of pure delight.\"[^2] Similarly, in the preceding Chapter 25 (\"Himalaya\"), he hails the mountain as \"rampart of the realm of Hindustan,\" a timeless sentinel evoking spiritual grandeur.[^3]\n\nBy Part 3, Chapter 25 (\"Wataniyat\"), however, Iqbal sharply critiques territorial nationalism (*wataniyat*) as a modern idol desecrating faith:\n\n> Of all these newer gods, **the greatest is the Nation**;  \n> The robe it wears is **Faith’s own final desecration**.[^4]\n\nHe urges Muslims to reject it: \"Your homeland is Islam,\" scorning confinement to \"one place\" as \"calamity\" and a barrier to prophetic universality, sowing rivalry and tearing \"God’s own creation...in pieces.\"[^5]\n\nThis juxtaposition stages a contradiction: the early poetic embrace of Hindustan as *watn* (homeland) versus the later philosophical demolition of nationalism as anti-Islamic parochialism. Iqbal's thought often reconciles such tensions through *khudi* (selfhood) and pan-Islamic universalism supplanting territorial ties, reflecting his shifting context amid rising communalism.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 26 \"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/26-hindustani-bachon-ka-qaumi-geet/translation/#p-da6786).\n[^2]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 26 [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/26-hindustani-bachon-ka-qaumi-geet/translation/#p-da6786-p-a9f72d).\n[^3]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Ch. 25 \"Himalaya\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-b8c905).\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 25 \"Wataniyat\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-79b1e9).\n[^5]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Ch. 25 [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-2737d5-p-a723b2).",
